<h2 id="what-is">What Is Advance Parole?</h2>
<p><strong>Advance Parole</strong> is a travel authorization issued by USCIS that allows a person with a pending <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status">Adjustment of Status (I-485)</SmartLink> application to leave the United States and return without abandoning their green card application.</p>
<p>Without Advance Parole, leaving the U.S. while your I-485 is pending is generally treated as <strong>voluntarily withdrawing your application</strong>. When you return, USCIS may find your I-485 abandoned and deny it — meaning you'd have to start the entire green card process over.</p>

<div class="art-warn">
  <strong>The single most important rule</strong>
  <p>Do not leave the U.S. while your I-485 is pending until you have your Advance Parole document physically in hand. A pending I-131 application does NOT authorize travel — only the approved, issued document does.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="who-needs">Who Needs Advance Parole</h2>
<p>You need Advance Parole if <strong>all three</strong> of these apply:</p>
<ul>
  <li>You are in the United States</li>
  <li>You have a pending I-485 Adjustment of Status application</li>
  <li>You want to travel outside the U.S. and return</li>
</ul>
<p>This commonly applies to:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>K-1 fiancé visa holders</strong> who married and filed for AOS — see the <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status-after-marriage">AOS after marriage guide</SmartLink></li>
  <li>Spouses who entered the U.S. on another visa and filed AOS while inside the country</li>
  <li>Anyone else with a pending I-485 who needs to travel internationally</li>
</ul>
<p>Note: If you hold a valid <strong>H-1B, L-1, or O-1</strong> visa alongside your pending I-485, you may be able to travel on that visa without Advance Parole. Consult an attorney if you're in this situation — the rules are nuanced.</p>

<h2 id="how-to-get">How to Get Advance Parole — Form I-131</h2>
<p>Advance Parole is requested on <strong>Form I-131</strong> (Application for Travel Document). The best approach is to file I-131 <em>concurrently</em> with your I-485 package:</p>

<table class="art-table">
  <thead><tr><th>Detail</th><th>Info</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Form number</td><td>I-131 (Application for Travel Document)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Filing fee</td><td>$0 when filed at the same time as I-485</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Where to file</td><td>Same package as I-485 (lockbox or online)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Processing time</td><td>3–6 months (2026 estimate)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>What you receive</td><td>Combo card — EAD + Advance Parole on one card</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Validity</td><td>Typically 2 years from issuance date</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<div class="art-info">
  <strong>File I-131 with your I-485 — never separately later</strong>
  <p>Filing I-131 concurrently with I-485 is free. If you file it separately after already submitting I-485, the fee is $630. Always include it in your initial filing package to save money and avoid delays in receiving travel authorization.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="combo-card">The Combo Card: EAD + Advance Parole</h2>
<p>USCIS currently issues a single <strong>combo card</strong> that serves as both your Employment Authorization Document (EAD) and Advance Parole document. This one card lets you:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Work legally in the United States (EAD function)</li>
  <li>Travel internationally and re-enter the U.S. (Advance Parole function)</li>
</ul>
<p>The combo card looks like a green card but says "Employment Authorization" on it. It includes your photo, fingerprint, and validity dates. Show it to your employer for I-9 verification and to CBP officers when returning from abroad.</p>
<p>Check your <SmartLink href="/adjustment-of-status-processing-time">AOS processing timeline</SmartLink> to understand where the EAD/combo card fits in the overall sequence — it's typically one of the first benefits you receive while your I-485 is still being processed.</p>

<h2 id="rules">Travel Rules With Advance Parole</h2>
<div class="art-tips">
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 01</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Have the physical card before you leave</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">The approved, physical combo card must be in your possession before departure. A USCIS approval notice alone is not sufficient — airlines and CBP require the actual card.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 02</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Check the expiration date before every trip</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">Your combo card has an expiration date. You must return to the U.S. before the card expires. If it expires while you're abroad, re-entry becomes complicated — plan trips with a buffer.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 03</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Carry your full document set</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">When traveling, bring your combo card, your passport, a copy of your I-485 receipt notice, and any other immigration documents. CBP officers may ask questions about your pending AOS at re-entry.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 04</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Don't miss your AOS interview while abroad</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">If USCIS schedules your AOS interview while you're traveling, you must return in time. A missed interview can delay or deny your case. Check case status at my.uscis.gov before any trip and plan return dates conservatively.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 05</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Some countries require a visa despite AP</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">Advance Parole is a U.S. document — it doesn't replace visas required by other countries. You still need to meet entry requirements of wherever you're traveling. Check visa requirements for your destination with your own passport.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-tip">
    <div class="art-tip-num">Rule 06</div>
    <div class="art-tip-title">Renew before it expires if I-485 is still pending</div>
    <div class="art-tip-desc">If your I-485 is still pending when your combo card is about to expire, file a renewal I-131 at least 6 months before expiration. USCIS issues automatic 180-day extensions when a timely renewal is filed.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="emergency">Emergency Travel Before Advance Parole Is Approved</h2>
<p>If you have a genuine emergency (death of an immediate family member, serious illness abroad) and your Advance Parole hasn't been issued yet, you have limited options:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>USCIS expedite request</strong> — call 1-800-375-5283 and request an expedite of your I-131 based on humanitarian need; bring documentation of the emergency</li>
  <li><strong>USCIS InfoPass / in-person appointment</strong> — request an emergency appointment at your local USCIS field office</li>
  <li><strong>U.S. embassy or consulate abroad</strong> — in extreme cases, officers can assist with re-entry on humanitarian grounds, though this is not guaranteed</li>
</ul>

<div class="art-warn">
  <strong>Consult an attorney before emergency travel</strong>
  <p>The risk of your I-485 being considered abandoned is real. An immigration attorney can advise you on your specific situation, help document the emergency, and potentially expedite the I-131 before you leave.</p>
</div>

<div class="art-cta-mid">
  <h3>Not sure if your situation requires Advance Parole?</h3>
  <p>H-1B holders, those with dual status, and K-1 holders have different rules. An attorney can tell you exactly what applies to your case.</p>
  <a href="#" class="art-btn" data-affiliate="attorney-consult">Get an Attorney Review →</a>
  <a href="/adjustment-of-status" class="art-btn-outline">Full AOS Guide</a>
</div>

<h2 id="return">Returning to the U.S. on Advance Parole</h2>
<p>When you return to the U.S. using your Advance Parole combo card, you re-enter as a <strong>parolee</strong> rather than on your original visa status. This is completely normal and expected — it doesn't harm your I-485 or immigration record.</p>
<p>At the border or airport:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Present your combo card and passport to the CBP officer</li>
  <li>You may be asked about your pending I-485 and the purpose of your trip</li>
  <li>The officer will admit you in "paroled" status — your I-485 continues processing</li>
  <li>Your I-94 will be updated to reflect your parole status</li>
</ul>
<p>After your green card is approved (either <SmartLink href="/conditional-green-card">conditional</SmartLink> or permanent), you no longer need Advance Parole — green card holders can travel freely and re-enter as lawful permanent residents.</p>

<h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="art-faq">
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What is Advance Parole?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>A USCIS travel document that lets you leave and re-enter the U.S. while your I-485 Adjustment of Status is pending — without abandoning your green card application.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long does Advance Parole take to get?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Filed concurrently with I-485, typically <strong>3–6 months</strong> in 2026. It's issued as a combo card combining EAD + Advance Parole. Do not travel until the physical card arrives.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">What happens if I leave the U.S. without Advance Parole?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Your I-485 is generally considered abandoned. USCIS may deny it when you return, requiring you to restart the green card process. Do not travel internationally without your approved Advance Parole card.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Can I travel before my Advance Parole is approved?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>No. A pending I-131 application does not authorize travel — only the issued combo card does. For emergencies, contact USCIS about an expedite request and consult an attorney before leaving.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">How long is Advance Parole valid?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>Typically <strong>2 years</strong> from issuance. If your I-485 is still pending when it expires, file a renewal I-131. USCIS issues automatic 180-day extensions when a timely renewal is filed.</p></div>
  </div>
  <div class="art-faq-item">
    <p class="art-faq-q">Does Advance Parole affect my status when I return?</p>
    <div class="art-faq-a"><p>You re-enter as a "parolee" rather than on your original visa. This is normal and expected — your I-485 continues processing without issue. Once your green card is approved, you enter as a lawful permanent resident.</p></div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="art-cta-dark">
  <h2>One step closer to your green card</h2>
  <p>Advance Parole is part of the broader Adjustment of Status process. See how every stage connects — from <SmartLink href="/biometrics-appointment">biometrics</SmartLink> to interview to green card.</p>
  <a href="/adjustment-of-status-processing-time" class="art-btn-white">Full AOS Timeline →</a>
  <a href="#" class="art-btn-ghost" data-affiliate="attorney-consult">Get Attorney Help</a>
</div>

</ArticleLayout>
